  <p>
    When you walk into a store, visit an office building, stay at a hotel, or even walk through a parking lot, the property owner has a legal obligation to keep the premises reasonably safe. That's not an opinion. That's Arizona law. When property owners ignore hazards, defer maintenance, or fail to address known dangers, they're gambling with your safety. Premises liability law exists to hold them accountable when that gamble injures someone.
  </p>

  <h2>The Duty of Care Framework</h2>

  <p>
    Arizona law categorizes visitors into three groups, and the duty of care a property owner owes depends on which group you fall into.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Invitees</strong> receive the highest level of protection. You're an invitee when you enter a property for the owner's benefit, typically as a customer or business visitor. Property owners must actively inspect their premises for hazards, fix dangerous conditions promptly, and warn invitees about any hazards that haven't been corrected yet.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Licensees</strong> are on the property with permission but for their own purposes, like social guests. Property owners must warn licensees about known hazards but aren't required to conduct proactive inspections.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Trespassers</strong> receive the least protection, but property owners still can't set traps or create intentionally dangerous conditions. Children who trespass receive additional protection under the attractive nuisance doctrine, which holds owners liable for hazards that predictably attract children, like unfenced swimming pools or abandoned equipment.
  </p>

  <h2>Commercial Property Claims</h2>

  <p>
    Commercial property owners owe the highest duty of care because their visitors are invitees. Shopping centers, grocery stores, restaurants, gas stations, movie theaters, gyms, and hotels all fall into this category.
  </p>

  <p>
    Common claims against commercial properties include wet floors without warning signs, uneven parking lot surfaces, falling merchandise, broken escalators and elevators, inadequate lighting in parking areas, and insufficient maintenance of walkways and entryways.
  </p>

  <p>
    In the West Valley, the rapid construction of new commercial developments in Buckeye, Goodyear, and Surprise sometimes outpaces the quality controls that prevent hazardous conditions. Construction defects, improperly graded surfaces, and missing safety features in newly built properties create liability for both the property owner and the developer.
  </p>

  <h2>Residential Property Claims</h2>

  <p>
    Landlords are responsible for maintaining common areas and building systems in a safe condition. That includes stairwells, hallways, parking lots, laundry rooms, pools, and fitness centers. When a tenant or visitor is injured because the landlord failed to maintain these areas, the landlord is liable.
  </p>

  <p>
    Common residential claims involve broken stairs or railings, poor lighting in common areas, malfunctioning gates or security systems, swimming pool hazards, pest infestations, and environmental hazards like mold or lead paint.
  </p>

  <h2>Inadequate Security Claims</h2>

  <p>
    Property owners who know about criminal activity on or near their property have a duty to provide reasonable security measures. That might mean adequate lighting, security cameras, fencing, gated access, or security personnel. When an owner ignores a known crime problem and someone gets assaulted, robbed, or otherwise victimized on the property, the owner shares liability.
  </p>

  <p>
    These claims are common in apartment complexes, parking garages, hotels, and convenience stores. We investigate crime data, prior incident reports, and the property's security history to establish what the owner knew and what they failed to do about it.
  </p>

  <h2>Government Property Claims</h2>

  <p>
    Injuries on government-owned property, such as public parks, sidewalks, government buildings, and schools, carry a critical deadline difference. You must file a notice of claim within 180 days under ARS 12-821.01. That's six months, not two years. Missing this deadline eliminates your right to sue the government entity entirely.
  </p>

  <p>
    Government entities aren't immune from premises liability in Arizona, but the claims process adds procedural requirements that don't apply to private property owners. We handle the notice requirements and navigate the government claims process.
  </p>

